</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Fumento:  Ignored Report Says EPA Wrong on Passive Smoking </title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a><center>
<i>12/7/95</i><hr><h2>Ignored Report Says EPA Wrong on Passive Smoking </h2>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/fumento.html"><i>Michael Fumento</i> </a>
</center><hr>

<P>

With a man who had torched three buildings  running around Boulder, 
Colorado city police were following smoke trails.  They caught their 
man, and he now faces a fine of $1,000 or 90 days in jail.  No, the 
perpetrator wasn't the arsonist (who was caught that same day); he was 
the owner of a bar  and a violator of Boulder's new anti-smoking law, 
one of the most draconian in the country.
<P>
The Boulder law goes way beyond mandating separate areas for smokers.  
Essentially it demands that smokers be kept away from non-smokers in 
hermetically-sealed rooms, as if they were the germ featured in the 
1971 movie The Andromeda Strain.  But a new report by the 
Congressional Research Service (CRS) finds that the basis for it, as 
well as all the other anti-smoking laws which have swept the country 
since December of 1992, is scientifically bankrupt.
<P>
This refutes a much-publicized 1992 study, conducted by the 
Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), which claimed as many as 3,000 
Americans die each year of lung cancer from somebody else's cigarette 
smoke. The EPA based its findings on a combined study (called a meta-
analysis) of 11 separate studies, which between them found 119 lung 
cancers among non-smoking spouses of smokers where 100 would be 
expected. Epidemiologists call this a "risk ratio" of 1.19. 
<P>
At the time, many people including myself criticized the EPA report, 
saying that such a small apparently increased risk (so tiny, in fact, 
that the medical community has rejected much larger ratios as being 
conclusive on other potential carcinogens) that the tiniest problem 
could throw the whole thing off.
<P>
We also questioned the EPA's use of a 90% confidence interval, meaning 
that there was a 10% possibility the results had been arrived at by 
chance.  The gold standard in epidemiology has always been a 95% 
confidence interval, leaving only a 5% possibility of a result 
occurring by chance.  Curiously, the Agency rejected that, in what 
appeared to be a rigging of the results. It was like moving the goal 
post to the three yard line because the football had fallen two yards 
short of a touchdown.
<P>
The new CRS report, which you're hearing about probably for the first 
time here because with the sole exception of the Washington Times (and 
an editorial in Investor's Business Daily) the media decided you 
didn't need to know about it, says we were right and the EPA was 
wrong.
<P>
 That report was produced in response to a proposed Occupational 
Safety and Health Administration ruling that would ban smoking in 
federal workplaces.  It found no basis for such a ban.
<P>
Instead, it said the EPA's meta-analysis showed that, "Even when 
overall risk is considered, it is a very small risk and is not 
statistically significant at the 95% level."
<P>
The CRS also analyzed four other recent passive smoking studies.  Of 
them, only one--by Dr. Elizabeth Fontham--showed a significant 
increased risk.  Two others showed no higher risk and a third showed 
only a slight, statistically insignificant risk.
<P>
As is, that's something of a wash.  But even the Fontham study may not 
actually show an increased risk, said the CRS.  This is because of 
something called "smoker misclassification."  Surveys show that some 
people who claim to be nonsmokers are actually current or former 
smokers.  The EPA has recognized this phenomenon and has built in a 
small safety margin to account for it in the Fontham study.  But 
evidence indicates this safety factor was probably too small, and CRS 
says "a small adjustment could render the overall Fontham  results 
statistically insignificant at the 95% level."
<P>
So the only truly significant positive study would have been rendered 
insignificant.
<P>
Moreover, the CRS noted that the other three studies didn't allow for 
unidentified smokers. Had they done so, the lack of evidence for 
smoking's hazards to innocent bystanders would have been even more 
obvious.   
<P>
The ultimate purpose of the campaign that culminated in the EPA report 
was never to protect non-smokers but to harass and intimidate smokers 
themselves into quitting.  Now it could be said that smokers were in 
effect not just hurting themselves but murdering non-smokers.  So what 
if it's not true?  The end--getting active smokers to quit--justifies 
the means.  Right?
<P>
Such paternalism is obnoxious.  Anybody with two brain cells to rub 
together knows that smoking is harmful and can be fatal. More than a 
hundred years before the famous 1964 surgeon general's report, 
cigarettes were known as "coffin nails." Smokers may be irrational, 
but irrationality within limits is protected in our society.
<P>
Meanwhile, where does such paternalism end?  One of the arresting 
officers in Boulder, a female, was quite corpulent.  (Trendy towns 
like Boulder are willing to overlook beefy cops if it means beefing up 
the number of female officers on the force.) Obesity is considered to 
cause 300,000 premature deaths a year, 100 times the EPA estimate for 
lung cancers caused by passive smoking.  Perhaps that officer should 
arrest the next waiter who puts a plate of Fettuccine Alfredo before 
her.  "Boy, you in a heap  o trouble for heapin' that pasta so high!"
<P>
Perhaps I shouldn't give them any ideas.
<P><P>
<i> Michael Fumento is a science correspondent for Reason Magazine.</i>
<P> <br><center><a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0">
</a></center></body></html>





 
