<html>
<head>
<title>The Passions of the Greenpeacers</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center>
<i>NEW YORK, SEPTEMBER 8</i>
<hr>
<h2>The Passions Of the Greenpeacers</h2><br>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/buckley.html"><b><i>William F. Buckley Jr.</i></b></a><hr><br></center>
 
Commentator/philosopher Herbert Agar had a term for it -- "the 
anarchic passion to smash." He was writing fifty years ago about 
whatever it is that causes some people, especially when young, to give 
vent to the impulse to wreck -- if necessary, the nearest thing in 
sight. The politicization of that impulse had a lot of help during 
this century from ideology, which seemed to give it some purpose. The 
young Bolsheviks destroying everything they could lay their hands on 
in St. Petersburg. The young fascists on a spree in Milan. The Nazis, 
who could objectify that passion to smash in search of anything 
Jewish.<p>

We have it now, that anarchic passion, and the animating instrument is 
nuclear -- well, nuclear anything. Most recently the decision by the 
French to conduct some nuclear tests in the South Pacific. But 
anything that has the word "nuclear" attached to it helps to bring on 
that same spirit. Not long ago Jane Fonda was enthralling the younger 
generation by her movie The China Syndrome, the hero of which was a 
nuclear meltdown that threatened, oh, the end of the world, or 
something very close to that. The Greenpeace movement is based on an 
undifferentiated hostility to everything nuclear, and it is having a 
wonderful time these days in Tahiti.<p>

The French are a highly utilitarian people, in ways commendable and 
not so commendable. They acknowledge force majeure, as when Hitler 
quickly and decisively proved that his army was better than their 
army: so they quickly surrendered, and got along with the occupiers 
without too much of a fuss, leaving it to the exiled Charles de Gaulle 
to help to mobilize Great Britain and the United States to effect 
French liberation.<p>

When nuclear power was shown to be a reasonable means of providing 
energy, the French, without much fuss, simply went nuclear, so much so 
that nearly 80 per cent of French electricity is nowadays generated by 
nuclear plants. In the Sixties, President de Gaulle decided that it 
was not prudent to depend on American nuclear missiles to serve as a 
dispositive deterrent to Soviet expansionism, so he developed what he 
called a force de frappe, something small enough to be manageable but 
deadly enough to discourage overt Soviet military aggression. 
President Chirac, thirty years later, was persuaded that one more set 
of tests was necessary to ascertain that French nuclear resources were 
authoritative. Evidently only that one series is deemed necessary to 
achieve the desired level of efficiency -- and safety -- because M. 
Chirac has declared that after the conclusion of these tests, in May, 
he will commit France never again to test nuclear weapons.<p>

Philip Shenon of the New York Times reports on the honeymoon of a 
Seattle dermatologist, Sonja Krejci, and her new husband, Dr. Bill 
Clark, bound for a romantic Polynesian resort island after a scheduled 
connection at Papeete. But when they landed, far from making their 
connecting flight, they were imprisoned in the airport building 
surrounded by rioters, tear gas, and smoke. At one point the rioters 
assaulted everyone with rocks and stones, causing Dr. Clark, who is an 
orthopedic surgeon, to consider the possibility of needing to use his 
professional resources to keep his bride alive. "At one point," 
reports Mr. Shenon, "some of the rioters found a bulldozer, 'and they 
just drove it right into the terminal building -- smashing cars and 
destroying the restaurant,"' as the poor doctor put it. An estimate of 
the damage done to the airport comes to $11 million. No estimate is 
yet in on how many honeymoons originally scheduled for Tahiti have 
been rescheduled elsewhere.<p>

A reader of the ongoing press reports on the activities of Greenpeace 
and others stops suddenly -- or might do so -- to ask: What is it the 
protestors fear? Are the French experiments, conducted 750 miles from 
Tahiti, endangering anybody in Tahiti? For that matter, are they 
endangering anybody or anything in Mururoa, the atoll used for the 
nuclear testing? Has anybody detected a rise in pollutants in the area 
where the first tests were undertaken? Has a whale been killed? Two 
whales? Has $11 million in damage been done to the sea surrounding 
Mururoa?<p>

The answer has to be No, for the simple reason that if it were Yes, we 
absolutely would have heard about it. The Greenpeace types desperately 
need a martyr. A poisoned ocean, a scarred sun -- something that 
points to Chernobyl. But there isn't anything there. Only the anarchic 
passion to smash. <p>
<br>
[<a href ="/townhall/columnists/welcome.html.cgi"> Columnists </a>]
<br>[<a href ="/nationalreview/welcome.html"> National Review </a>]
</body>
</html>

