<html>

<head>

<title>Buckley:  Grave Business In Los Angeles</title>

</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">

<center>

<i>NEW YORK, SEPTEMBER 29</i>

<hr>

<h2>Grave Business In Los Angeles</h2><br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/buckley.html"><b><i>William F. Buckley Jr.</i></b></a><hr><br></center>


 

The cliche has it that anything Johnnie Cochran et al. can do to 
spring their client is okay. If this is so, they have certainly abided 
by that liberty. At the end of Thursday, Mr. Cochran had done his best 
to convince the jurors that either O. J. Simpson is guiltless and 
should be set free, and perhaps lionized in an effort to expiate the 
troubles he has seen, or else the jurors don't believe in the Bible, 
in the Constitution, or that Hitler went too far.
                                              <P>
Now pay close attention to what is going on. The cameras take us to an 
impromptu press conference called by Fred Goldman, who is the father 
of Ron, the young man killed alongside Nicole. Mr. Goldman is teeming 
with resentment and fires both barrels. "He's talking about racism and 
he's talking about hate? Who does he connect himself with? This man 
ought to be ashamed of himself to talk among decent human beings. He 
is one of the most disgusting human beings I have ever had to listen 
to in my life. Because of racism, we should put aside all other 
thoughts, all other reason, and set his murdering client free?"
                                    <P>
Well, that statement brought counterfire from the other side. The 
elder sister of O.J. took the floor for the first time to plead the 
innocence and virtue of her brother. But she said something more 
important, really, than that she was standing by for sibling loyalty. 
She said that "only" the jurors could pronounce the truth on all these 
questions being raised. The truth, of course, on whether O.J. killed 
Nicole and Goldman. But, derivatively, the case Mr. Cochran was 
pleading: that Mark Fuhrman, the racist detective, was 
indistinguishable from Adolf Hitler, that the Los Angeles police are 
happy to send an innocent man to jail for life, even though they know 
him not to be guilty. The point here is that, once again, we are asked 
to see the jury as an instrument for uncovering the Truth. To believe 
this is to surrender to the powers of hypnotists.
                         <P>
That of course is what Johnnie Cochran and Barry Scheck have attempted 
to do, to hypnotize the jury, and the inducements have been about as 
comprehensive as they can be. If you believe that Hitler was evil, 
then you have to fight Hitlerism in America, which is embodied in Mark 
Fuhrman, who uncovered the glove with O.J.'s blood on it, which glove 
had been placed there by Hitler. If you believe that the Los Angeles 
Police Department did some sloppy work, then you must believe that its 
motive in doing so was to advance the fraudulent case against O.J. If 
you believe, with Luke, that little lies often indicate bigger lies, 
then you must vindicate O.J. You cannot, simultaneously, believe in 
O.J.'s guilt, and in St. Luke's divine inspiration.
                <P>
It does remind one -- does it not? -- of some of the great show trials 
of the Thirties, conducted by Stalin. When it was charged that 
Bukharin was guilty of counterrevolutionary activity, not only the 
Soviet court nodded its acquiescent head, but a lot of other people 
did too, including American intellectuals. It required the labors of 
the Dewey Commission and some hard analysis by a generation of 
scholars to set the record absolutely right. In Moscow the court was 
the creature of Josef Stalin and would have ruled, if told to do so, 
that the earth is flat. The question seriously arises whether the 
court, in Los Angeles, becomes the creature of Johnnie Cochran, whose 
use of apocalyptic rhetoric transforms the question, Did he do it, or 
did he not do it? into the question, Do you believe in God, do you not 
believe in God? Into, Do you believe in civil liberties, do you not 
believe in civil liberties? 
                                                                                <P>
If one had confidence in Judge Ito one might hope that he could move 
the jury back to reality, to relieve the jury of any notion that it is 
complicit in Nazism if it finds O.J. guilty. How would the Soviet 
court have reacted if it had been given, the day before its ruling, 
Arthur Koestler's Darkness at Noon to read? But Judge Ito is in over 
his head, and just possibly it is true that Western judicial procedure 
is in over its head. If a persuasive shaman is left free to seduce a 
bleary, near-dead-from-fatigue jury that theirs is to justify death, 
or to save Western idealism, then we are talking about something very 
different from the administration of justice.
<p>

<br>
<center>
