<html>
<head>
<title>Buckley: 'Ideology' On Our Mind -- 2/20/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<i>
NEW YORK, FEBRUARY 20, 1996
</i>

<h2>
'Ideology' On Our Mind
</h2>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/
buckley
.html">
William F. Buckley Jr.
</a>

<P>
The point has been made, most specifically by Washington Post 
columnist David Broder, that the principal candidates for President 
shrink from "ideology." Thus Mr. Clinton separates himself from the 
Gephardt wing of the Democratic Party, and Senator Dole allows a 
certain amount of water to pass between him and Newt Gingrich. 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The whole matter of ideology both vexes and enlightens political 
thought. The word is used differently in political discourse. The 
average voter will seek some consistency, or appearance of 
consistency, in a candidate's platform. The philosopher scorns 
ideology because too often it overwhelms reason, prudence, philosophy. 
The word was French and came out of the crucible of the French 
Revolution, which was the bloody complement of the American 
Revolution. 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Senator Phil Gramm has generally been considered the most consistent 
of the conservatives running for the Presidency this year. If you 
believe A, that government activity ought not to replace non-
government activity except when required, you will believe B, that the 
government should not run the local pizza parlor. Ideology is a body 
of ideas reflecting the social needs and aspirations of an individual, 
a group, a class, or a culture (American Heritage Dictionary). But 
ideology is also "a set of doctrines or beliefs" that form the basis 
of a political, economic, or other system. If your position on a 
political question derives from a doctrine, then you are committed to 
subordinating your political position to your doctrinal position. 
Otherwise, you tend to wobble. Some wobbling is an aspect of political 
opportunism -- Senator Gramm in Iowa did not criticize federal 
subsidies of the ethanol program, which is a relic of the Department 
of Energy's extravagances. Sometimes it is an extra-ideological 
deference to reality (let the Federal Government help Los Angeles 
after its earthquake). 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
But then we begin to line up other political questions, to be 
scrutinized ideologically. And it is here that the word "presumption" 
is useful. If you believe A -- that the government should stay out of 
the way -- you believe this either dogmatically or empirically. Was it 
right to intervene in Somalia? No, if the undertaking was designed to 
transform Somalian culture -- we should know that this can't be done; 
we tried and gave up making the world safe for democracy. Yes, if the 
single objective was to prevent mass starvation. Presumptively, stay 
out. 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
What about tariffs? Long ago, conservative doctrine shaped up in favor 
of free trade. This was, indeed, an extension of anti-government 
doctrine. A tariff is a tax paid by one American for the benefit of 
another American. But it is more than that, because it denies to the 
American consumer the advantage of competitive bidding, and 
derivatively deprives the foreigner of the wherewithal to patronize 
American production. 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
What about educational vouchers? Conservatives will in almost every 
situation honor the supremacy of the consumer over the regulator, so 
that if Mrs. Jones wants that school for her child, not the public 
school, the conservative would seek to expedite the choice. . . . Is 
that question ideologically related to school prayer? Yes, it is: the 
state should not intrude its wishes, or its restrictions, in the 
culture of free men, freely associating with one another. 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Immigration? National independence? The state is by no means useless, 
as the anarchists insist. The state is a "natural" institution, and 
exercises its authority in matters that relate to the commonweal when 
these are clearly national concerns. The flow of immigration into a 
country is self-evidently the proper concern of the state inasmuch as 
only its agents can say Yes or No at the border. And the traffic needs 
to be regulated because there is a greater demand than supply. Mr. Fox 
Butterfield finished his memorable book on Communist China by quoting 
one Chinese who said that if the means to do so could be found, every 
Chinese would go to America to live. "Even the lamp posts would go." 
And sovereignty asserts a recognition that the world has yet to see 
(or even envision) a cultural unity that combines in acceptable 
priorities what we have called the American proposition.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
So, Mr. Clinton edges away from ideologues in his own party (every 
problem is a state problem, and every dollar earned is forfeit to the 
state's agenda), and Senator Dole tries to shape an ideologically 
lucid opposition that appeals both to voters whose dogma is 
conservative, and to those whose inclinations are conservative. It is 
tough going, as much an art as a discipline.

<P><P>

<P>
<center>
[<a href ="/townhall/columnists/"> Columnists </a>]

<br>[<a href ="/nationalreview/"> National Review </a> ]

<br>

</blockquote></blockquote>




<P> <br>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map">
<img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0">
</a></center>
<P>
</body>
