HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Thursday, 09-Jan-97 15:14:31 GMT
Last-modified: Wednesday, 22-May-96 15:55:36 GMT
Content-length: 6483
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>

<title>Rockwell: China: Trade Yes, Aid No  -- 4/22/96
</title>

</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<i>
 April 22, 1996
</I>
<h2> China: Trade Yes, Aid No 
</h2>



<a href="/townhall/columnists/rockwell.html">Llewellyn H. Rockwell, Jr.</a>
<p>
What's so difficult about China? The political class seems  
intent on reviving the Cold War, but every issue before us can be  
solved by a quick reflection on the basic principles of classical  
liberalism, which happen to coincide with America's traditions as  
well as common sense. The rule with China, as with every other  
country, should be this simple: trade, not aid.  
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The trouble with Most Favored Nation status is that it  
conflates the two categories. It gives the recipient access to  
our markets and ours to theirs, with low tariffs both ways, which  
is as it should be. However, it also makes MFN governments  
eligible for grants, loans, and guarantees from the World Bank  
and the International Monetary Fund. Those are indirectly and  
primarily funded by U.S. taxpayers.   
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
Have these grants and loans ever done any good in the long  
run? There's not a single case. Rich countries have gotten along  
without them just fine. Poor countries get strapped with debt,  
and have to accept the policy terms of the lending agencies. More  
often than not, that means Keynesian-style fiscal policy, heavy  
regulation, laborious labor laws, and tax increases. That is not  
a recipe for prosperity.  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
So by all means, end aid from these agencies to China, and 
everywhere else. At the same time, there is no good reason to  
impose trade sanctions. They merely restrict the rights of  
American consumers and producers to buy and sell in the most  
favorable places. If that's France and Germany, fine. If it's  
China and Cuba, that's fine too. With the Cold War over, it's  
time to separate economic policy and foreign policy.  
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
That the political class is suddenly ganging up on China is  
particularly ironic. Here's a communist government that has  
liberalized its economy to a striking degree. More trade will  
push the process further, and might even ensure some measure of  
political liberalization as well.  
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
Yet the litany of reasons why China should be considered a  
"rogue state" grows ever longer. Its government squelches civil  
liberties. It doesn't enforce U.S. property rights. It encourages  
abortion. It threatens its neighbors. Bad, bad, China.  
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
But by those standards, the U.S. government looks pretty  
roguish too. Federal police agencies are no well-known respecters  
of human rights. As for property rights, they took quite a  
beating on April 15 this year. The U.S. government routinely  
engages in land seizures in the name swamp protection, and it  
promotes abortion with tax dollars.  
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
Is this, to use Cold War language, the horrible practice of  
seeing a "moral equivalence" between U.S. democratic and foreign 
authoritarian ones? Not at all. As Americans, we have  
a moral obligation to concentrate on the beam in our eye, not the  
splinter in someone else's.  
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
The biggest problem is hypocrisy. We not only trade with,  
but give massive aid to, governments around the world that  
mistreat their own people, kill innocents outside their borders,  
and refuse to recognize even rudimentary liberties. Why single  
out China?  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
China may tolerate the copying of films and compact discs.  
The question is: why should American consumers be denied access  
to goods from China because American exporters are unhappy with  
Chinese copyright laws? It is the business of U.S. exporters, not  
the U.S. government, to protect overseas profits.  
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
All of this flows from a simple proposition, the very basis  
of the free enterprise system: economics is the business of  
business, not government. If the U.S. government has any role, it  
is to protect life, liberty, and property here at home. Forcing  
exports on others, punishing evildoers abroad, or centrally  
planning the world trading system only invites trouble.  
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
But isn't China threatening Taiwan, and isn't that grounds  
to wage a trade war? We only started hearing about the grave  
threat to Taiwan a few weeks before the Taiwanese ruling party  
was up for reelection. The central point in its platform is that  
China is a grave threat. Is it? If holding war games off its own  
shores is a hostile act, what about U.S. war games with Japan and  
Korea off China? Indeed, on the threatening of small countries by  
big ones, Panama, Cuba, Nicaragua, Haiti, and the Dominican  
Republic might have something to say.  
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
But let's assume China is planning an invasion of Taiwan,  
highly improbable given the relative balance of military power.  
What then? As regrettable as that might be, the U.S. cannot  
guarantee every State Department-approved border in the world.  
Let Taiwan provide for its own security, as it has amply done. It  
is not up to Americans to be taxed, or die, for foreign regimes. 
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The last time the West tried to force its dominion and  
products on China, the issue was opium, and it led to vast  
unrest, the overthrow of the monarchy, and the eventual communist  
takeover. That brings us to another principle derived from the  
classical-liberal tradition: we cannot fully anticipate the bad  
consequences of government intervention, so we ought to prevent  
it where we can. 
<p><P>
<i>
Llewellyn H. Rockwell, Jr., is president of the Ludwig von Mises 
Institute in Auburn, Alabama.
<i>

</blockquote></blockquote>




