<html>
<head>
<title>Taxpayers Subsidize AARP -- Heritage </title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<b>Government Integrity Project Report No. 1<br>
June 12, 1995</b>
<p>
<center><h2>TAXPAYERS SUBSIDIZE AARP</h2><br>
<b>Senior Citizens Group Receives $86 Million from Uncle Sam</b><br>

By <a href="/heritage/staff/wittmann.htm">Marshall Wittmann</a><br>
Senior Fellow in Congressional Affairs<br>
<p>
Charles P. Griffin<br>
Deputy House Liaison</center><br>
<p>

The $86 million that the American Association of Retired Persons acknowledged receiving in federal funding for 1993 through various grant programs represents approximately one-quarter of its annual expenditures. AARP's sources of funding range from programs for the elderly to millions of dollars annually to provide clerical support to the EPA. Many senior citizens groups receive almost all of their federal funding in one lump sum payment from the Senior Community Service Employment Program, but AARP also benefits from numerous smaller grants.
<p>
Following is a brief breakdown of most of AARP's federal funding from July 1993 to June 1994. Reference numbers are those contained in the <i>Catalog of Federal Domestic Assistance</i>:
<p><ul>
<li>The largest single source of AARP funding is the Department of Labor/Employment Training Administration's Senior Community Service Employment Program. This one account provides about $49 million per year to AARP's bank account. More than $300 million of the $400 million appropriated for Program Year 1994 went to nine seniors organizations and the Forest Service, with the remainder going to the states. [17.235]
<p>
<li>AARP is a major beneficiary of the EPA's Senior Environmental Employment Program. The annual appropriation is $45 million, from which approximately 265 grants are made. AARP appears to receive approximately $20 million from this program. The AARP provides support to almost every regional office of the EPA, as well as to most divisions within the Washington headquarters. [66.508]
<p>
<li>AARP receives approximately $4.6 million per year under the Treasury Department/Internal Revenue Service's Tax Counseling for the Elderly Program. This represents the lion's share of the grant's annual appropriation. [21.006]
<p>
<li>AARP receives $75,000 per year from the Centers for Disease Control to develop "comprehensive breast and cervical cancer early detection programs."  The grant requirements in the <i>Catalog </i>state this money is available only to "official State health agencies of the United States" and its territories. Other groups funded in this manner include the National Education Association, the American Federation of Teachers, and the American Nurses Association (ANA). [93.919]
</ul>
<br>
<BR><HR WIDTH="30%"><BR><CENTER><A HREF="/heritage/hbut.map"><IMG SRC="/heritage/hbut.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A></CENTER></body>
</html>
  
