<html>
<head>
<title>Rockwell: "Public Sector" Racket -- 04/21/96
</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<i>
April 21, 1996
</i>


<h2>"Public Sector" Racket 
</h2>
Llewellyn Rockwell
<P>


The term "public sector" is highly misleading. It's supposed  
to refer to the government, that well-known public servant, in  
contrast to the "private sector," the greedy and selfish market.  

<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
 
But the opposite is the case. In the "private sector," all  
activity is focussed on serving the public, people helping people  
get quality goods and services at the best price. A business that  
loses sight of its consumers is quickly outcompeted by one that  
serves the public better. The market is the true public sector.  
 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

On the other hand, government is obsessively focussed on  
itself and its private, internal, bureaucratic interests. It  
doesn't engage in productive enterprise, there are no regular  
consumers of its "services," it is owned by no one in particular,  
and it doesn't worry about profit and loss.  
 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

Government's primary if not exclusive function is to  
redistribute wealth from one group to another by force. The  
people, the very ones involuntarily funding the government, are  
seen as chumps and menaces, and used as pawns in social  
experiments and power grabs. 
 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

All this comes clear when you compare the way any private  
company works with, say, the Department of Housing and Urban  
Development. In the most recent outrage, HUD decided it should  
blow up its housing projects in downtown Baltimore and move the  
residents to pricey homes in the suburbs, at fantastic taxpayer  
expense. 
 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

This demented scheme--which will drive down property values,  
increase crime, and unsettle whole communities--is at war with  
the public interest. That's why it's generated an explosion of  
resistance among homeowners in the Baltimore area. Especially  
peeved are new suburbanites, who worked hard to get away from the  
inner city.  
 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

Just who benefits from this scheme? Power-mad bureaucrats  
who see their mandate as tearing up the social pea patch, and the  
contractors and social workers who live off the ensuing  
destruction. These are private, not public, interests.  
 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

The market, in contrast, is the peaceful and fully  
accountable public servant. Capitalists produce houses and  
apartments for every social group. If we were sticklers in our 
use of language, we would call what the market achieves "public  
housing," since its purpose is not to destroy, but to create  
housing options for everyone at the least possible expense.  
 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

Here's another example. Which is more anxious to serve the  
public: the government's mail operation, or the myriad of private  
delivery services? You don't have to be an expert to know. UPS 
and Fedex men toil with packages piled high, racing from place to  
place, competing to provide ever better service.  
 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

The U.S. Postal Service is so bad that it changed its name  
(it used to be Post Office) and logo (from a mailbox to an  
eagle's head) to avoid ridicule. The service gets worse (I'm old  
enough to remember twice-daily delivery), the price always goes  
up (especially on business), and the whining never stops. Can we 
imagine Fedex employees complaining about too much business, as  
the postal people do during the Christmas season?   
  
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

No, public service is not the Postal Service's strength. But  
it has mastered the art of lobbying. That's why, despite the  
blather about being "revolutionary," this Congress hasn't even  
considered repealing the unamerican laws that prohibit  
first-class mail competition.  
 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

Like all government bureaucracies, the Postal Service has no  
real owners, and most of its "customers" have no choice. The  
offices are so unpleasant that one of last year's best performing  
stocks was a company that takes your letters and packages to the  
P.O. so you don't have to.  
 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

So the Postal Service blows millions on ads designed to  
bamboozle. One new campaign claims it's "a very businesslike  
business." Why? Because it's so big, the 33rd largest "company"  
in the world, having moved up a notch after the Politburo was  
downsized.  
 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

Although the government claims that its private interests  
are really the public interest, it is busy destroying private  
industries that truly do serve the public. If the Justice  
Department brings suit against a business for "discriminating"  
against some privileged group, for example, it's as good as dead.  
 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

Worse, Congress has called on the nation's tax-collecting  
public servants to share their jobs with non-government lawyers,  
so they can scarf up more private revenue. 
 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

Thanks to this perverse "privatization," a private-sector  
profession will be paid by a public-sector agency to loot private  
property for the private interests of phony public servants. Oh,  
for those simpler, better days before government ruined our  
language.
 
<P><P>

</blockquote></blockquote>


<I>Llewellyn H. Rockwell, Jr., is president of the Ludwig von Mises 
Institute in Auburn, Ala.</I> <P> 

<br><center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map">
<img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0">
</a></center>
<P>
</body>
</html>

