<html>
<head>
<title>Rockwell: Hillary's Revenge -- 4/24/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<i>
 APRIL 25, 1996
</i>

<h2>
Hillary's Revenge
</h2>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/rockwell.html">
 Llewellyn H. Rockwell, Jr.
</a>

<P>

Hillary Clinton has won a victory in the Senate. The  
Senate's health care bill, which passed unanimously, is not as  
flashy and detailed as her failed legislation. But the central  
principle is the same: the government, one way or another, should  
guarantee health care to everyone.  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Recall that Mrs. Clinton found herself on the receiving end  
of a propaganda blitz. She was denounced as a Marxist who wanted  
to centrally plan the economy, destroy small business, and take  
away freedom of choice.  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
This was sweet music to lovers of free enterprise. Was the  
Republican Party, which in the past has backed big government  
medical reforms, at last making principled arguments? Corporate,  
medical, and insurance lobbies--also soft on government  
intervention--even joined in the attack.  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
People and publications not usually prone to criticize  
statism sounded like libertarian purists. Even the New Republic  
ran a detailed, point-by-point attack on the White House plan.  
Thanks to these efforts, we were spared a nightmarish plot to  
nationalize one-seventh of the economy.  
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
And yet, ominously, several provisions--some of the most  
socialistic ones in the Clinton plan--escaped deep criticism. For  
example, insurance companies would be forbidden from refusing, or  
charging higher premiums for, customers who would drive them to  
bankruptcy. That is, insurers could not take account of  
"preexisting conditions," as the lingo has it.  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Zoom forward one year. This provision ends up as the core of  
the Republican health care bill. If automotive or housing  
insurance couldn't "discriminate," costs would zoom and clients  
would have less of an incentive to care for their property. So  
too will this rule destroy the character of insurance in the  
medical industry.  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Real insurance relies on actuarial tables, premiums that  
reflect risk (adjusted for any reason), and carefully grouped  
risk pools. A fat, cigar-smoking coach potato will have higher  
premiums than a member of the high-school swim team. If it is  
illegal to make a distinction, it's not business but welfare.  
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
So title I, section 101 of this bill calls for "Guaranteed  
Availability of Health Coverage." Group health plans "may not  
establish eligibility, continuation, enrollment, or contributions  
requirements" based on "health status, medical condition, claims  
experience, receipt of health care, medical history, evidence of  
insurability, or disability of a participants or beneficiary." 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
What is an insurance company supposed to do if it can't  
assess the risk? Just dish out the big bucks. But can an insurer  
discreetly avoid certain professions based on their preponderance  
of sick employees? Nope: an insurance company "may not decline to" 
insure a person or group that demands it.  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
In this system, insurance companies cease to be market  
operations, working on the basis of profit and loss, and instead  
become middlemen in a socialist enterprise. But the Senate will  
take socialism only so far: pregnancy, unlike AIDS and other  
sexually transmitted diseases, is expressly excluded as a  
"pre-existing condition" (I,103,(a)).  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
If people's premiums can't go up and they can't be rejected  
based on bad behavior, there is less to be gained by preventive  
care. That's how the plan eliminates some of the incentives for  
people to take care of themselves and not overuse medical  
services.  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The companies doing the insuring are even restricted in  
their ability to quit providing insurance. They have to give 180  
days notice if a plan is going to be discontinued (I,110(b)2).  
Then they have to wait five years before offering the plan again.  
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
Remember the price controls implicit in the Clinton bill?  
You'll find them here too. The Secretary of Health and Human  
Services will devise "Federal standards that limit the variation  
in health insurance premiums" so that they will be "reasonably  
priced" (I,112,(a)).  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Remember the bureaucracies in the Clinton health bill? This  
plan instructs the states, as overseen by the feds, to create  
"Health Plan Purchasing Coalitions" to determine the size and  
demographics of each risk pool (I, 131). The burden of proof is  
on the Coalition to show that it is not "discriminating."  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
In fact, this bill differs from the Clinton plan in only two  
ways: it is less ambitious and less honest. The Clinton plan  
included specific provisions that tried to account for every  
possible contingency. The Senate bill asserts broad  
principles--cheap health care for all!--but doesn't bother to  
specify how it's going to come about.  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Both plans are crazy, but is it wackier to wreck a sector  
with specific socialist instructions or broad socialist  
principles? Is it worse to specify the outcome or rig the game to  
ensure a certain outcome? Both are intolerable, although--as it  
turned out--only one could be enacted.  
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
The bill's unanimous support is a measure not of merit, but  
of hypocrisy. For a year, the Republican Party dragged Hillary  
Clinton's name through the mud. Fine. She deserved it. But she  
also deserves an apology from everyone who denounced her bill and  
backed this one. 
<P> 

<I> 
Llewellyn H. Rockwell, Jr., is president of the Ludwig von Mises  
Institute in Auburn, Alabama.<I>
<br>
<P><P>
</blockquote></blockquote>




<P> <br>
