<html>
<title>Stand for Children or Last Stand For Big Government -- Heritage</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<b>Government Integrity Project Report No. 9<br>
May 31, 1996</b>
<center>




<h2><i>STAND FOR CHILDREN OR LAST STAND FOR BIG GOVERNMENT?</I></h2>

<a href="/heritage/staff/weinstein.html">Kenneth R. Weinstein</a><br>
Director, Government Reform Project<br>
<a href="/heritage">The Heritage Foundation</a>
<hr width=50%>
</center><p>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;
On June 1, 1996, national attention will be focused on the "Stand for Children" march on the Mall in Washington, D.C. The ostensible purpose of this march is one that all Americans would support: "to celebrate children and those who struggle every day to raise them. Organizers claim that between 200,000 and one million people will gather at the Lincoln Memorial in a non-partisan call to action. Unfortunately, however, the principal action likely to be called for is an increase in federal spending. One reason is that at least 102 of the sponsoring organizations are federal grant recipients, receiving an aggregate of over $392 million annually. 
<p>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;
A slick public relations campaign has generated dozens of news stories hailing the Stand for Children's call to affirm our responsibility as families, individuals, communities, and as a national community for improving the quality of life of children. But the camera-ready banners and young families with children expected on the Mall are not the entire story. An examination of organizations endorsing the event makes it clear that the Stand for Children rally is not a nonpartisan, pro-children march; it might better be dubbed the "Last Stand for Big Government.
<p>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;
The event is being convened by the Children's Defense Fund (CDF), once chaired by no less a proponent of big government than Hillary Rodham Clinton. The president of the CDF is Marian Wright Edelman, a long-time friend of Mrs. Clinton, and chief opponent of efforts in the 104th Congress to reform welfare. In 1973, Edelman frankly admitted that because she could no longer stir up interest in government programs by speaking of poor people, she had decided to emphasize children in her rhetoric. Children, after all, might be a very effective way to broaden the base of change.<sup>1</sup>
<p>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;
Many other groups apparently have decided that Edelman was talking about more than just pocket change. The list of 426 organizations endorsing the Stand for Children looks like a Who's Who of federally funded organizations. Over one hundred of the endorsing groups received a total of at least $392 million in FY 1993-1994 alone. The total government subsidy to these organizations is actually higher, since this $392 million excludes grants to some affiliates as well as all funds received from state or local governments. Each of these organizations has a clear interest in assuring that it can continue to rely on money from the American taxpayer. 
<p>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;
One government agency, the Agriculture Department's Cooperative State Research, Education and Extension Service (CSREES), a $931,784,000 federal program in FY 1995, has signed on as a national endorser of the program under the guise of its outreach program, Families 4H and Nutrition. The Freddie Mac Foundation, an arm of the federally chartered Freddie Mac Corporation, also is sponsoring the march.
<p>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;
Lobbyists appear to be another big constituency of the Stand for Children. Lobbying arms for federal programs costing over $7 billion annually have endorsed the march. Among these are the National and Community Service Coalition (chief lobbyist for President Clinton's $400 million national service program, AmeriCorps), the National Head Start Center (lobbyist for the $2.2 billion Head Start program), and the National Association of WIC Directors (the Special Supplemental Food Program for Women, Infants, and Children, a $3.6 billion federal program in FY 1995). Families U.S.A., the key lobbyist in the effort to support Bill Clinton's government-run health care plan, is also a march endorser. 
<p>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;
In addition to grant recipients, lobbyists, and government agencies, at least 20 national organizations comprised of government employees, such as the U.S. Conference of City Human Services Officials and the National Association of School Psychologists, will be participating in the march. 
<p>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;
Further proof of the partisan character of the march is the fact that the AFL-CIO, which is spending $35 million in mandatory union dues to defeat conservative Members of Congress in the 1996 elections, is actively promoting it. The AFL-CIO and 33 of its affiliated unions serve as national endorsing organizations for the Stand for Children. At this past February's meeting of the AFL-CIO Executive Committee, when union leaders decided to launch their efforts to take back the Congress, two special guests were invited to speak: Steve Protulis of the National Council of Senior Citizens, fresh from the MediScare campaign on Capitol Hill, and Marian Wright Edelman, who spoke about the Stand for Children rally. The June 1 March obviously embodies the AFL-CIO's determination to defend the welfare state.
<p>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;
More evidence that the Stand is another attempt to broaden the base of support for big government is the fact that at least 50 liberal and activist left organizations with no special focus on children, including Americans for Democratic Action, Women Strike for Peace, the Gay and Lesbian Victory Fund, Greenpeace, the National Rainbow Coalition, and Zero Population Growth, serve as co-sponsors.
<p>
&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;
The groups behind the Stand for Children march seek to present their rally as a spontaneous, nonpartisan, grassroots expression of altruism towards America's youth. Nothing could be further from the truth. The Stand for Children rally offers a continuation of a calculated strategy launched in the early 1970s to expand the welfare state, a strategy used effectively to oppose efforts by the 104th Congress to balance the federal budget.  While many participating in the march no doubt have the best interests of children at heart, many of the sponsoring organizations have a clear self-interest in promoting government spending as the best way to Stand for Children.
<P>
<b>Endnotes:</b>
<ol>
<li>    Mickey Kaus, "The Godmother: What's Wrong with Marian Wright Edelman," <I>The New Republic</I>, February 15, 1993, 
  p. 21.
</ol>
<p>
