<html>
<head>
<title>National Trust Lobbies Congress -- Heritage </title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<b>Government Integrity Project Report No. 3<br>
July 11, 1995<br></b> 
<p>
<center> 
<h2>FEDERALLY SUBSIDIZED NATIONAL TRUST LOBBIES CONGRESS</H2><br>
By <a href="/heritage/staff/wittmann.htm">Marshall Wittmann</a><br>
Senior Fellow in Congressional Affairs<br>
<p>
Charles P. Griffin<br>
Deputy House Liaison</CENTER><br>
<p>
The National Trust for Historic Preservation (NTHP) receives approximately $7 million each year from the American taxpayers.  As part of its effort to set budget priorities and balance the budget, the House Appropriations Committee has decided to phase out federal funding for this organization over the next two years. An amendment by Representative Tom DeLay (R-TX) that would have eliminated the subsidy in just one year was defeated by voice vote in committee.
<p>
	In recent years, the Trust has lobbied Congress to expand the historic rehabilitation tax credit (at a cost of $1.4 billion over five years, according to the Trust itself1) and has fought economic development nationwide, including a proposed Disney theme park in Virginia.2  It should come as no surprise that the Trust appears to have mobilized its forces to oppose these proposed cuts in its federal support.
<p>
	In a June 28, 1995, letter to members of the House of Representatives, Trust President Richard Moe declares that "Congress has given the National Trust a central role in the federal historic preservation program under our 1949 charter and the National Historic Preservation Act, as passed in 1966 and amended in 1992."  Despite this self-described pseudo-governmental role, the organization has chosen to mount a full-scale lobbying campaign against the funding reduction.

<blockquote><b>"VOTE NO ON AMENDMENT BY REP. DELAY TO ELIMINATE  FUNDING
FOR THE NATIONAL TRUST FOR HISTORIC PRESERVATION"</b></blockquote>
<p>
declares the headline on the National Trust's letter. Attached to the two-page text of the letter is a two-page target list of members who voted against cutting the NTHP's funding in 1993. 
<p>
	The National Trust for Historic Preservation's letter clearly shows the trouble with taxpayer-subsidized political advocacy.  In its fight to continue feeding at the public trough, the Trust has given the American people a good look at their tax dollars at work.
<p>
<a href="/heritage/staff/wittmann.htm">Marshall Wittmann</a><br>
Senior Fellow in Congressional Affairs
<p>
Charles P. Griffin<br>
Deputy House Liaison<hr>
<i>The Government Integrity Project examines the practice of permitting tax-exempt organizations that engage in political or legislative advocacy to receive funds from the federal government.</i><br>

<BR><HR WIDTH="30%"><BR><CENTER><A HREF="/heritage/hbut.map"><IMG SRC="/heritage/hbut.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A></CENTER></body>
</html>
1  Charlene Prost,  "Historic Preservation Trust Seeks to Gain New Backers,"  <i>St. Louis Post-Dispatch, </i> October 5, 1993, p. 13B.<br>
2  Editorial, "The War of the Subsidies," <i> The Washington Times</i>, May 6, 1994, p. A22.<br>




